Query sent to /graphql endpoint:

query IntrospectionQuery {
  __schema {
    types {
      name
      description
      fields {
        name
        description
        type { name }
      }
    }
  }
}

Response reveals: user payment methods, internal role enumerations, database field mappings, and privileged mutation endpoints - demonstrating information is publicly accessible without authentication.

remediation:
1. Disable introspection in production: Set introspection: false in GraphQL server config. 2. Implement authentication check: Wrap introspection behind authentication middleware. 3. Example (Apollo Server):

const server = new ApolloServer({
  typeDefs,
  resolvers,
  introspection: process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production',
  plugins: {
    didResolveOperation(context) {
      if (!context.request.user && context.operationName === 'IntrospectionQuery') {
        throw new Error('Introspection disabled');
      }
    }
  }
});

4. Alternatively, use graphql-armor or similar middleware for fine-grained control. 5. Regularly audit schema exposure via automated introspection queries in CI/CD.

Authorization Server Implementation:
```javascript
// Generate cryptographically secure random state
const crypto = require('crypto');
const state = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
// Store in server-side session (NOT client-side)
req.session.oauthState = state;
// Include in authorization URL
const authUrl = `https://provider.com/oauth/authorize?client_id=${clientId}&redirect_uri=${redirectUri}&response_type=code&state=${state}`;

// Callback handler - validate state parameter
app.get('/callback', (req, res) => {
  if (!req.query.state || req.query.state !== req.session.oauthState) {
    return res.status(403).send('Invalid state parameter');
  }
  // Proceed with token exchange only if state matches
});
```
Use cryptographically secure random generation and server-side session storage. Validate state on every callback.

